We established a health and demographic surveillance system in a rural area of 
western Kenya to measure the burden of infectious diseases and evaluate public 
health interventions. After a baseline census, all 33,990 households were 
visited every four months. We collected data on educational attainment, 
socioeconomic status, pediatric outpatient visits, causes of death in children, 
